[[Image:Floyd 99 Edited.PNG|right|thumb|300px|[[Hurricane Floyd]] ten hours prior to its [[North Carolina]] landfall; Floyd caused the worst modern disaster in the state<ref>{{cite web|author=Federal Emergency Management Agency|year=2000|title=Approaching One Year, North Carolina Floyd Assistance More Than $1.9 Billion|accessdate=2007-12-14|url=http://www.fema.gov/news/newsrelease.fema?id=9089}}</ref>]]
The '''list of North Carolina hurricanes''' includes 397&nbsp;[[tropical cyclone|tropical]] or [[subtropical cyclone]]s that have affected the [[U.S. state]] of [[North Carolina]]. Due to its location, many hurricanes have hit the state directly, and numerous hurricanes have passed near or through North Carolina in its history; the state is ranked fourth, after [[Florida]], [[Texas]], and [[Louisiana]], in the number of cyclones that produced hurricane force winds in a U.S. state.<ref name="chron">{{cite web|author=Hurricane Research Division|year=2008|title=Chronological List of All Hurricanes which Affected the Continental United States: 1851-2005|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|accessdate=2008-04-03|url=http://www.aoml.noaa.gov/hrd/hurdat/ushurrlist18512007.txt}}</ref><ref name="change">{{cite web|author=Hurricane Research Division|year=2006|title=Documentation of Atlantic Tropical Cyclones Changes in HURDAT|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|accessdate=2008-01-31|url=http://www.aoml.noaa.gov/hrd/hurdat/metadata_master.html}}</ref> Hurricanes in North Carolina history are responsible for over $11&nbsp;billion in damage (2008&nbsp;USD) and almost 1,000&nbsp;total fatalities.

== Climatology ==
According to statistical hurricane research between 1886 and 1996 by the North Carolina State Climatology Office, a tropical cyclone makes [[landfall (meteorology)|landfall]] along the coastline about once every four years. An estimated 17.5&nbsp;percent of all [[Atlantic hurricane|Atlantic]] tropical cyclones have affected the state.<ref name="ncclimate"/> Additionally, the remnants of a few [[Pacific hurricane|Pacific]] tropical cyclones impacted the state.<ref>{{cite web|author=David Roth|year=2008|title=Tropical Cyclone Rainfall for the Southeast|publisher=Hydrometeorological Prediction Center|accessdate=2008-04-03|url=http://www.hpc.ncep.noaa.gov/tropical/rain/tcsoutheast.html}}</ref> [[Cape Hatteras]] is most affected by storms within the state, though [[Cape Lookout]] and [[Cape Fear]] are also regularly impacted; the increased activity in three areas is because it protrudes from elsewhere along the the Atlantic coastline.<ref name="ncclimate">{{cite web|author=State Climate Office of North Carolina|year=2006|title=Hurricanes in North Carolina|accessdate=2008-04-03|url=http://www.nc-climate.ncsu.edu/print/8}}</ref> After Southern Florida, Cape Hatteras has the lowest return period, or the frequency at which a certain intensity or category of hurricane can be expected within 86&nbsp;[[statute mile|mi]] (139&nbsp;[[kilometre|km]]) of a given location, in the country.<ref>{{cite web|author=National Hurricane Center|year=2006|title=Tropical Cyclone Climatology|accessdate=2007-10-02|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/pastprofile.shtml}}</ref> As the [[Outer Banks]] are a narrow strip of low-lying land, hurricanes occasionally leave portions of the land partially or fully submerged.<ref>{{cite web|author=Sprol.com|date=2005-09-15|title=When will a Category Five Hurricane strike the Outer Banks?|accessdate=2008-03-04|url=http://www.sprol.com/?p=259}}</ref> Additionally, the remnants of inland tropical cyclones have produced flooding and landslides in the state's western region.<ref name="0069rain">{{cite web|author=William Haggard, Thaddeus Bilton, and Harold Crutcher|publisher=Journal of Applied Meteorology|year=1973|title=Maximum Rainfall from Tropical Cyclone Stems which Cross the Appalachians|format=PDF|accessdate=2008-03-23|url=http://ams.allenpress.com/archive/1520-0450/12/1/pdf/i1520-0450-12-1-50.pdf}}</ref>

Tropical cyclones have affected North Carolina in every month between May and December; about 35&nbsp;percent of the storms impacted the state in September, and 80&nbsp;percent affected the state between August and October, which coincides with the peak of the hurricane season. The earliest storm to affect the state was [[Subtropical Storm Andrea (2007)|Subtropical Storm Andrea]] on [[May 7]], [[2007]], and the latest was a tropical storm that moved across the Outer Banks on [[December 2]], [[1925]]. The strongest storm to strike the state was [[Hurricane Hazel]] in 1954, which made landfall as a [[List of Category 4 Atlantic hurricanes|Category 4]] hurricane on the [[Saffir-Simpson Hurricane Scale]].<ref name="hurdat">{{cite web|author=Hurricane Research Division|year=2007|title=Atlantic hurricane best track|publisher=[[NOAA]]|accessdate=2008-04-03|url=http://www.aoml.noaa.gov/hrd/hurdat/easyhurdat_5107.html}}</ref>

== Pre-1900 ==
[[Image:North carolina topographic.jpg|right|300px|thumb|Topographic map of [[North Carolina]]]]
{{main|List of North Carolina hurricanes (pre&ndash;1900)}}
The list of North Carolina hurricanes before 1900 encompasses 139&nbsp;[[tropical cyclone]]s that affected the [[U.S. state]] of [[North Carolina]]. Collectively, cyclones in North Carolina during the time period resulted in over 775&nbsp;direct fatalities during the period. Seven cyclones affected the state in the [[1893 Atlantic hurricane season|1893 season]], which was the year with the most tropical cyclones impacting the state during the time period. From the beginning of the official Atlantic hurricane record in 1851 to 1899, there were 12&nbsp;years without a known tropical cyclone affecting the state.

Historical data prior to 1700 is sparse due to lack of significant European settlements along the coastline; the few storms listed are largely records from [[Roanoke Colony]] and later the [[Province of Carolina]]. Modern meteorologists believe early storms were tropical cyclones, though due to the time period confirmation is impossible.<ref name="nc">{{cite web|author=James E. Hudgins|year=2000|title=Tropical Cyclones Affecting North Carolina since 1566 - An Historical Perspective|publisher=Blacksburg, Virginia National Weather Service|accessdate=2007-12-18|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20070311045226/http://repository.wrclib.noaa.gov/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1002&context=nws_tech_memos}}</ref> One theory explaining the disappearance of Roanoke Colony suggests a hurricane destroyed the village, though there is no evidence to prove the theory. It is considered unlikely due to lack of damage to a fence around the village, on which the villagers left an inscription.<ref>{{cite web|author=Jarid Goodman|title=The Lost Colony of Roanoke, 1588|accessdate=2007-12-18|url=http://theshadowlands.net/roanoke.htm}}</ref>

==1900&ndash;1949==
[[Image:Theb2559.jpg|right|thumb|Damage from [[1933 Outer Banks hurricane]]]]
{{main|List of North Carolina hurricanes (1900&ndash;1949)}}
Between 1900 and 1949, 75&nbsp;tropical cyclones or their remnants affected the state. Collectively, cyclones in North Carolina during that time period resulted in 53&nbsp;total fatalities during the period, as well as about $328&nbsp;million in damage (2008&nbsp;[[United States dollar|USD]]). Tropical cyclone affected the state in all but nine seasons. In the [[1916 Atlantic hurricane season|1916 season]], five storms affected the state, which was the season with the most storms impacting the state.<!--Data based on the article--> The strongest hurricanes to affect the state during the time period were the [[1933 Outer Banks hurricane]] and the [[1944 Great Atlantic Hurricane]], which produced winds of Category&nbsp;3 status on the [[Saffir-Simpson Hurricane Scale]] within the state.<ref name="chron"/> The 1933 Outer Banks hurricane was the deadliest hurricane in the state during the time period, which killed 21&nbsp;people.<ref>{{cite web|author=Mary Souder|year=1933|title=Severe Local Storms, September 1933|publisher=U.S. Weather Bureau|accessdate=2008-03-28|url=http://docs.lib.noaa.gov/rescue/mwr/061/mwr-061-09-0291.pdf|format=PDF}}</ref> The remnants of a [[Georgia-South Carolina Hurricane of 1940|hurricane in 1940]] dropped heavy rainfall in the state, which caused over $150&nbsp;million in damage (2008&nbsp;USD) from flooding and landslides.<ref>{{cite news|author=Millsboro Daily News|date=1940-08-16|title=Floods Surge Toward Surge|accessdate=2008-03-23|url=http://www.thehurricanearchive.com/Viewer.aspx?img=51700375_clean&firstvisit=true&src=search&currentResult=4&currentPage=0}}</ref>

==1950&ndash;1979==
[[Image:Hurricane Connie Radar.gif|right|thumb|200px|Radar image of [[Hurricane Connie]] near North Carolina]]
{{main|List of North Carolina hurricanes (1950&ndash;1979)}}
A total of 79&nbsp;[[tropical cyclone|tropical]] or [[subtropical cyclone]]s affected North Carolina between 1950 and 1979. Collectively, cyclones during the time period resulted in 37&nbsp;total fatalities during the period, as well as about $3&nbsp;billion in damage (2008&nbsp;USD). A cyclone affected the state in every year during the time period, and in three seasons a total of five cyclones impacted the state.<!--Data based on article--> The strongest hurricane to hit the state during the time period was [[Hurricane Hazel]], which struck the state as a Category 4 hurricane on the [[Saffir-Simpson Hurricane Scale]]. Hazel was both the costliest and deadliest cyclone during the period, causing over $1&nbsp;billion in damage (2008&nbsp;USD) and 19&nbsp;deaths.<ref>{{cite web|author=NOAA Coastal Services Center|year=1999|title=New Hanover County, North Carolina Case Study on Hurricane Hazel|accessdate=2008-02-16|url=http://www.csc.noaa.gov/products/nchaz/htm/hazel.htm}}</ref> Most storms affected the state in September, though cyclones impacted the state between May and October.

== 1980&ndash;Present ==
[[Image:46 9 21 03 14.jpg|right|thumb|250px|New inlet created by [[Hurricane Isabel]] (USGS)]]
{{main|List of North Carolina hurricanes (1980&ndash;present)}}
The period from 1980 to the present<!--as of 2007--> encompasses 104&nbsp;[[tropical cyclone|tropical]] or [[subtropical cyclone]]s that affected the state. Collectively, cyclones in North Carolina during the time period resulted in over $10&nbsp;billion in damage (2007&nbsp;[[USD]]), primarily from hurricanes [[Hurricane Fran|Fran]] and [[Hurricane Floyd|Floyd]]. Additionally, tropical cyclones in North Carolina were responsible for 75&nbsp;direct fatalities and at least 44&nbsp;indirect casualties during the period. Eight cyclones affected the state in the [[1985 Atlantic hurricane season|1985 season]], which was the year with the most tropical cyclones impacting the state. Every year included at least one tropical cyclone affecting the state.<!--Data based on article-->

The strongest hurricane to hit the state during the time period was Hurricane Fran in 1996, which struck near [[Wilmington, North Carolina|Wilmington]] as a Category 3 hurricane on the [[Saffir-Simpson Hurricane Scale]]; [[Hurricane Emily (1993)|Hurricane Emily]] in 1993 brushed the [[Outer Banks]] also as a Category 3 hurricane.<ref name="chron"/> The deadliest hurricane during the period was Hurricane Floyd in 1999, which caused 35&nbsp;fatalities and record&ndash;breaking flooding in the eastern portion of the state.<ref>{{cite web|author=U.S. Department of Commerce|year=2000|title=Hurricane Floyd Floods of September 1999|publisher=NOAA|accessdate=2007-12-13 |url=http://www.weather.gov/om/assessments/pdfs/floyd.pdf|format=PDF}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=National Climatic Data Center|year=1999|title=Climate-Watch, September 1999|accessdate=2007-12-22|url=http://lwf.ncdc.noaa.gov/oa/climate/extremes/1999/september/extremes0999.html}}</ref>

